WeRateDogs Twitter Analysis¶

Introduction¶

The purpose of this study is to ingest Twitter data from a variety of sources and formats, assess it for quality and tidyness, clean and analyze the data. Since the collection of this data was not through a random experiment, findings are NOT assumed to have causality.

"Data for this project came from the archive of twitter user @dog_rates archive known as WeRateDogs." Users send the account pictures of their dogs and they receive a witty response and a rating of the dog. The rating ranges from 0 to 13 (denominator) and is compared to 10 as the numerator. WeRateDogs does not follow rigid rating. They have values above 13.

Twitter provided Udacity permission to use the archive and Twitter also granted this author "Student" access to Tweety (their API) to download the tweet data associated with this project.

Training for techiques used in this analysis came from Udacity Data Analysis class and from pandas and matplotlib documentation at the following URLs:

https://classroom.udacity.com/nanodegrees/nd002/parts/af503f34-9646-4795-a916-190ebc82cb4a

https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.Series.str.extract.html?highlight=str%20extract#pandas.Series.str.extract

https://matplotlib.org/3.1.0/gallery/index.html

https://stackoverflow.com/search?q=save+output+as+.png+matplotlib

Information on WeRate dogs also obatined from Wikipedia at the following link: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WeRateDogs

# import modules needed to work with this dataset
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
%matplotlib inline
import requests
In [2]:
# read the twitter-archive-enhanced csv file into a data frame called twitter_archive_enhanced
twitter_archive_enhanced = pd.read_csv('twitter-archive-enhanced.csv')
In [3]:
# create a copy of twitter_archive_enhanced to be used with the tweepy API
tw1 = twitter_archive_enhanced
In [4]:
# The code to perform this step was provided by Udacity at the following link: 
# https://video.udacity-data.com/topher/2018/November/5be5fb4c_twitter-api/twitter-api.py

# this imports the tweepy application to be used by pandas
import tweepy
# this is the authorization module required by Twitter
from tweepy import OAuthHandler
# this allows the reading of json files
import json
# thi creates a timer as Twitter limits the amount of data that can be pulled within a timeframe
from timeit import default_timer as timer
# 
# These are hidden to comply with Twitter's API terms and conditions
consumer_key = 'HIDDEN'
consumer_secret = 'HIDDEN'
access_token = 'HIDDEN'
access_secret = 'HIDDEN'

auth = OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_secret)

api = tweepy.API(auth, wait_on_rate_limit=True)

# this establishes the list of tweet ids, taken from twitter-archive-enhanced.csv that will be compared to 
# the twitter json data on the Tweepy platform.
tweet_ids = tw1.tweet_id.values
len(tweet_ids)

# Query Twitter's API for JSON data for each tweet ID in the Twitter archive
count = 0
fails_dict = {}
start = timer()
# Save each tweet's returned JSON as a new line in a .txt file and writes it out as tweet_json.txt
with open('tweet_json.txt', 'w') as outfile:
    # This loop will likely take 20-30 minutes to run because of Twitter's rate limit
    for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
        count += 1
        print(str(count) + ": " + str(tweet_id))
        try:
            tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id, tweet_mode='extended')
            print("Success")
            json.dump(tweet._json, outfile)
            outfile.write('\n')
        except tweepy.TweepError as e:
            print("Fail")
            fails_dict[tweet_id] = e
            pass
end = timer()
print(end - start)
print(fails_dict)

Next, we need to remove any tweet records that were retweets. The retweeted_status_id should provide a guide to removal of the records.

Furthering the understanding of the variables, we will look at the doggo, puppo, pupper, and floofer fields to see how it is populated.

In [17]:
# displays the contents of doggo

Out[17]:
None     2259
doggo      97
Name: doggo, dtype: int64
In [18]:

Out[18]:

puppo      30
Name: puppo, dtype: int64
In [19]:
# displays the contents of pupper

Out[19]:
None      2099
pupper     257
Name: pupper, dtype: int64
In [20]:
# displays the contents of floofer
twitter_archive_enhanced['floofer'].value_counts()
Out[20]:
None       2346
floofer      10
Name: floofer, dtype: int64

We can see that doggo has the value of doggo if the animal is identified in that stage, otherwise it is populated with None. This is a tidy data issue. doggo, puppo, pupper, and floofer should be moved under a single variable, called development_stage. This eliminates additional variables.

Looking at the rating numerator, we see values as high as 1776. The WeRateDogs Wikipedia page indicated the ratings numerator is is up to 13, however, the rating structure is not followed rigidly and is considered one of the things appealing to followers. In this study, the high rating records were not removed and the analysis will not utilize the rating information.

The following issues are visible in from the result above:

  • tweet ID should be an integer64, not a float
  • in_reply_to_status_id and in_reply_to_user_id should be an integer64, not float
  • timestamp should be datetime, no object
  • there appear to be 181 retweeted items based on retweeted_status_id, retweeted_status_user_id, and retweeted_status_timestamp
  • retweeted status timestamp should be datetime, not object

Checking to see if retweeted_status_timestamp has values populated as this dield has the potential to be used to remove retweets.

Looking at the file above, we see the following issues:

  • id should be renamed tweet_id
  • in_reply_to_status_id, in_reply_to_status_id_str, in_reply_to_user_id, and in_reply_to_user_id_str are float. in_reply_to_status_id and in_reply_to_user_id should be integer. in_reply_to_status_id_str and in_reply_to_user_id should be string
  • geo appears to have no values
  • coordinates appers to have no values
  • place appears to have only 1 value
  • contributors appears to have no values
  • there are 163 retweeted_status records. Need to delete them.
  • quoted_status_id should be an integer and seems to have very few records (26)
  • quoted status_id_str should be a string and seems to have very few records (26)

Looking at the full text, the following can be observed:

  • There are tweet users at the beginning of the text field (@serial, @MrRoles, etc. These could be stripped out into their own column.
  • Rating is included in text, but could be moved into its own field. Since it was, it can be removed from this field.
  • the Twitter url for the tweet is included. It should be stripped and moved into its own field.

Next, let's look at the lang variable.

In [37]:
# displays the contents of the lang variable
tweets['lang'].value_counts()
Out[37]:
en     2313
und       7
nl        3
in        3
es        1
tl        1
ro        1
et        1
eu        1
Name: lang, dtype: int64

Spell out the different languages of the tweets. en = English, es = Spanish , tl = Tagalong , ro = Romanian , nl = Nederlands, in = Indonesian, et = Estonian, und = Undetermined, eu = Basque

ISO 639-1 codes are used by Tweepy. I found the codes for all of the above except "und" which I took to be undetermined. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_ISO_639-1_codes#ET https://www.sitepoint.com/iso-2-letter-language-codes.

In [38]:
# use query to display dataset contents when lang = und
tweets.query('lang == "und"')

Looking at the data, above, we see the following:

  • The picture is contained in jpg_url
  • p1, p2, p3 represent the predicted dog breed. Need to spell out prediction.
  • p1_conf, p2_conf, p3_conf represent confidence in the prediction. Need to spell out prediction.
  • Notice that p1, p2 and p3 dog names are lower_case. Need to make first letter uppercase.
  • Breeds with two words have an underscore. Should be a space.

Next, we need to see if there are any duplicate columns in the datasets. The code below will check.

In [54]:
# check for duplicate columns in all three of the datasets
all_columns = pd.Series(list(twitter_archive_enhanced) + list(image_predictions) + list(tweets))
all_columns[all_columns.duplicated()]
Out[54]:
17                 tweet_id
37                   source
38    in_reply_to_status_id
40      in_reply_to_user_id
dtype: object

tweet_id, source, in_reply_to_status_id and in_reply_to_user_id are duplicated. Since tweet_id = id is common to all files, will need to keep that as the primary key for all datasets.

The quality and tidyness issues I discovered are shown below:

Quality Issues:¶

In the twitter_archive_enhanced file:¶

1) rating_numerator: Values ranging from 0 to 1776. they should be in the range from 0-13. Need to further investigate. The WeRateDogs Wikipedia page indicated the ratings numerator is is up to 13, however, the rating structure is not followed rigidly and is considered one of the things appealing to followers. In this study, the high rating records were not removed and the analysis will not utilize the rating information

2) rating_denominator: Values exceed 10. Need to further investigate these values. As stated above, we will not alter the ratings.

3) there are a large number of names equal to "None". Need to see if we can obtain any of these from the text file.

3) There are 181 rows that are retweets in the twitter_archive_enhanced file. We will need to remove these. They can be indentified using "retweeted_status" variable.

4) Dog's name: There are a number of records with a names of "None", "an", 'the","very", "quite","one", "just", "actually","mad", "not", "officially", "infuriating", "unacceptable, "light", "his", "old", "all, "my", "such", "by, "this", "space", "life", and "a".

5) The the tweet_id should be an object/string as it is not to be used in calculting statistics. It is meant to identify the tweet.

6) The in_reply_to_status_id and in_reply_to_user_id should be an string/object, not float.

7) Retweet_count and favorite_count are float64. They should be changed to integer as they are counts.

8) retweeted_status should be an object/string not float.

9) retweeted_status_timestam should be date/time, not object

10) using the rating numerator and rating denominator, divide to calculate the rating.

In the image_predictions file:¶

11) There are 543 images in the file that are not a picture of a dog. Need to remove these from the data.

12) Dog names in column "pl" are not capitalized in all cases.

13) Dog names should be categorical, not boolean

14) twitter_archive_enhanced "timestamp variable is an object. It should be date/time.

15) twitter_arhchive_enhanced "retweeted_status_timestamp" is an object. It should be converted to date/time.

16) clarify the purpose of the p1,p2,p3 variables by spelling out "prediction."

17) There are a number of rows where the puppy's "name" is equal to 'None'. Try to find the names in the texts.

In the tweet-json.txt file:¶

18) There are a number of rows that are retweets. We will need to remove these. They can be indentified using "retweeted_status" variable.

19) id should be renamed tweet_id

20) in_reply_to_status_id, in_reply_to_status_id_str, in_reply_to_user_id, and in_reply_to_user_id_str are float and should be converted to integer.

21) quoted_status_id should be an integer and seems to have very few records (26)

22) quoted status_id_str should be an object/string

23) The source is included in this file as well as twitter_archive_enhanced. Drop "source" from cleaned_tweets.

24) Remove the "lang" column. It does not provide additional value to this study. All tweets appear to be either english or jibberish.

25) Remove the truncated column as the only value is "False".

26) The text field contains two data elements (The rating response and the tweet URL. The tweet URL should be separated.

Tidy Data Issues:¶

In the twitter_archive_enhanced file:¶

1) We can see that doggo has the value of doggo if the animal is identified in that stage, otherwise it is populated with None. Best approach is to move doggo, puppo, pupper, and floofer under a single variable, called development_stage. This eliminates additional variables.

In the tweet-json.txt file:¶

2) tweets and twitter_archive_enhanced have the following duplicate column names: tweet_id, source, in_reply_to_status_id, and in_reply_to_user_id. Plan to delete keep tweet_id as it is common to all files and delete the in_reply_to_status_id and in_reply_to_user_id from the twitter_archive_enhanced file. tweets seems to have a fuller table and it makes sense it should go with that table.

3) Remove the geo, coordinates, place and contributors columns becaues they provide little to no data.

4) Remove the display_text_range column as it only provides the display text range

5) Remove the entities column as it does not provide any data that will be used in the analysis.

6) Drop is_quote_status as it does not add value to the analysis

7) The quoted_status_permalink does not appear to add value to the analysis.

Cleaning¶

We start by making copies of the original data files.

In [62]:
# create copies of the original datasets
cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced = twitter_archive_enhanced.copy(deep=False)
cleaned_tweets = tweets.copy(deep=False)
cleaned_image_predictions = image_predictions.copy(deep=False)

Define¶

There are a number of rows that are retweets. We will need to remove these. They can be indentified using "retweeted_status" variable.

Code¶

In [63]:
# Identify number of rows of cleaned_tweets before cleaning
cleaned_tweets.shape[0]
Out[63]:
2331
In [64]:
# strips out rows where retweeted_status is not null
cleaned_tweets = cleaned_tweets[cleaned_tweets.retweeted_status.isnull()]
cleaned_tweets = cleaned_tweets[cleaned_tweets.in_reply_to_status_id.isnull()]

Define¶

Avoid errors by ensuring that retweet_count and favorite count are equal to 0 when the value is null.

Code¶

In [74]:
# ensures retweet_count equal to zero if not greater than zero
cleaned_tweets.loc[(cleaned_tweets['retweet_count'] < 0) | (cleaned_tweets['retweet_count'].isnull()), 'retweet_count'] = 0
In [75]:
# ensures favorite_count equal to zero if not greater than zero
cleaned_tweets.loc[(cleaned_tweets['favorite_count'] < 0) | (cleaned_tweets['favorite_count'].isnull()), 'favorite_count'] = 0

Define¶

In the twitter_archive_enhanced file, the tweet_id should be an object/string as it is not to be used in calculting statistics. It is meant to identify the tweet. We will change it later. For now, need to change it to an integer64 as it will affect Microsoft Excel when imported as a CSV (the scientific notation strips off the last few digits in Excel).

Code¶

In [91]:
# change data type for tweet_id in the cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced, cleaned_tweets and image_predictions datasets
cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced['tweet_id'] = cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced['tweet_id'].astype('int64')
cleaned_tweets['tweet_id'] = cleaned_tweets['tweet_id'].astype('int64')
cleaned_image_predictions['tweet_id'] = cleaned_image_predictions['tweet_id'].astype('int64')
# change timestamp data type to datetime
cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced['timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced['timestamp'])

cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced_v1= pd.merge(cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced, nameless, how='left', on='tweet_id')

Define¶

The text field contains two data elements (The rating response and the tweet URL. The tweet URL should be separated.

Code¶

In [130]:
# split text into additional columns
cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced_v1['text1'] = cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced_v1['text'].str.split('https:', expand=True)
In [131]:
# split text into additional columns
cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced_v1['twitter_URLs'] = cleaned_twitter_archive_enhanced_v1.text.apply(lambda x : x.strip().split(' ')[-1])

Define¶

Ensure that retweet_count and favorite_count do not have any null values as a result of the merge.

Code¶

In [151]:
# ensure that null values were set to zero 
twitter_archive_master.loc[(twitter_archive_master['retweet_count'] < 0) | (twitter_archive_master['retweet_count'].isnull()), 'retweet_count'] = 0
twitter_archive_master.loc[(twitter_archive_master['favorite_count'] < 0) | (twitter_archive_master['favorite_count'].isnull()), 'favorite_count'] = 0
In [152]:
# change float to integer for retweet_count 
twitter_archive_master['retweet_count'] = twitter_archive_master['retweet_count'].astype('int64', errors='raise')
In [153]:
# change float to integer for favorite_count
twitter_archive_master['favorite_count'] = twitter_archive_master['favorite_count'].astype('int64', errors='raise')

Test¶

In [154]:
# look for null values
r_count_check['retweet_count'] = twitter_archive_master['retweet_count'].isnull()
